    <a href="#mission-11">11</a>
    <a href="#mission-12">12</a>
    <div class="nav-line"></div>
  </nav>
  <section class="lesson-container">
    
    <div id="intro" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Ready to start CSS?</h2>
        <p>
           Hey! You made it! How did you feel about HTML? Think it's boring? Bland? Well, CSS is where we start designing and bringing our dreams to fruition. HTML is the fabric, but CSS is the dye, the sequins, and the tailoring! 
            <br/><br/>
            Please keep in mind in order to earn your certificate you must take notes and send in your notes to us so that we know you completed the required learning documentation. You must use Google Docs. It makes the process easier and helps us give you your certificate in a timely fashion. 
            The linked textbook sections are also not the ONLY parts of the reading, you must finish the associated readings with each section. 
</p>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-1" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 1: Thinking Like Your Favorite Magazine</h2>
        <p>
           Personally, I really liked the now defunct Pinky Magazine. Maybe you're more into Kaltblut or Self Service...or Vogue! Whatever your personal style is, you can create it with Cascading Style Sheets (CSS). 
            <br/><br/>
            When you flip through a high-fashion magazine, you don't just read the words. You notice the glossy backgrounds, the elegant spacing, the bold colors, and the gorgeous fonts. That "aesthetic" isn't an accident—it's meticulously coded. CSS is what takes our structured HTML mannequin and dresses it up for the runway.
        </p>
 
    </div>

    <div id="mission-2" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 2: The First Stitches (CSS Basics)</h2>
        <p>
            Before we can add the rhinestones, we need to know how to thread the needle. In CSS, we use <strong>selectors</strong> to tell the browser exactly <em>which</em> piece of HTML fabric we want to style. 
            <br/><br/>
            Want to dye all the paragraphs pink? You select the <strong>p</strong> tag. Want to style just the collar of your dress? You give that specific HTML element a <strong>class</strong> (like <strong>.collar</strong>) or an <strong>id</strong> (like <strong>#statement-collar</strong>) and select it in your CSS file. You then open up some curly braces {{ }} and start writing your style rules inside. Time to build your first beautifully styled menu!
        </p>

       <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-what-is-css/what-is-css" target="_blank" class="view-btn">01 // WHAT IS CSS?</a>
             <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-basic-css/review-basic-css" target="_blank" class="view-btn">02 // CSS FUNDAMENTALS</a>
             <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-basic-css-by-building-a-cafe-menu/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">03 // BUILD A CAFE MENU</a>
           <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-blog-post-card/lab-blog-post-card" target="_blank" class="view-btn">04 // DESIGN A BLOG POST CARD</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-3" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 3: The Pink Palette (Color Theory)</h2>
        <p>
            Color theory is tech theory! We don't just type the word "pink" and call it a day. We are web designers! We use precise dye mixtures. 
            <br/><br/>
            In CSS, you'll meet  <strong>Hex codes</strong> (like <strong>#e41e81</strong>, which is the gorgeous hot pink we use here at P.C.C.),  <strong>RGB</strong> (Red, Green, Blue mixtures), and  <strong>HSL</strong> (Hue, Saturation, Lightness). Knowing how to mix these digital dyes is what separates a basic website from a visually stunning digital editorial. Let's learn how to paint the web!
        </p>

        <div class="resource-links">
  <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-colors-in-css/what-is-color-theory-in-design" target="_blank" class="view-btn">05 // COLOR THEORY</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-css-colors/review-css-colors" target="_blank" class="view-btn">06 // CSS COLORS FUNDAMENTALS</a>
  <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-colored-markers/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">07 // COLORED MARKERS LAB</a>
  <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-colored-boxes/set-of-colored-boxes" target="_blank" class="view-btn">08 // DESIGN YOUR OWN COLORED BOXES</a>

        </div>
    </div>

   <div id="mission-4" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 4: Typography & Google Fonts</h2>
        <p>
            Typography is the actual voice of your website. If your website is wearing a Chanel suit, you can't have it speaking in Comic Sans (unless you're going for deep irony, but let's master the rules before we break them).
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>
We link directly to  <strong>Google Fonts</strong> to import gorgeous, custom typefaces. You'll learn how to adjust the <strong>font-family</strong>, <strong>font-size</strong>, <strong>font-weight</strong> (how bold or delicate the text is), and line spacing so your text reads exactly like a professional magazine spread. Let's practice by styling a typography-heavy layout!
</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
<a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-css-fonts/what-are-the-fundamentals-of-typography" target="_blank" class="view-btn">09 // CSS FONTS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-typography-by-building-a-nutrition-label/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">10 // TYPOGRAPHY LAB</a>
  <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-css-typography/review-css-typography" target="_blank" class="view-btn">11 // TYPOGRAPHY FUNDAMENTALS</a>
  <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-newspaper-article/build-a-newspaper-article" target="_blank" class="view-btn">12 // BUILD A NEWSPAPER </a>

        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-5" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 5: Tailoring (The Box Model)</h2>
        <p>
          Every single thing you build in HTML is actually just a rectangular box. Even if a picture looks perfectly round, the browser sees a box! To make things look elegant and not squished together, you have to tailor the  <strong>CSS Box Model</strong>.
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>
Think of it like this: <br/>
 <strong>Content:</strong> You.<br/>
 <strong>Padding:</strong> Your cozy inner coat lining. It's the space <em>inside</em> the box, keeping the content away from the edges.<br/>
 <strong>Border:</strong> The physical seam or hem of the coat.<br/>
 <strong>Margin:</strong> Your personal space on the runway. It pushes <em>other</em> elements away from your box.<br/>
Let's practice getting our padding and margins tailored to perfection.
</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
<a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-css-transforms-overflow-and-filters/what-is-overflow-in-css" target="_blank" class="view-btn">13 // CSS TRANSFORMS, OVERFLOW, AND FILTERS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-the-css-box-model-by-building-a-rothko-painting/step-1" "target="_blank" class="view-btn">14 // THE BOX MODEL LAB</a>
 
 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-css-layout-and-effects/review-css-layout-and-effects" "target="_blank" class="view-btn">15 // CSS LAYOUTS AND EFFECTS</a>
 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-confidential-email-page/build-a-confidential-email-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">16 // SECRET EMAIL PAGE</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-6" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 6: Layout Choreography (Flexbox)</h2>
        <p>
           Back in the early days of the web, getting two pictures to sit nicely next to each other was a nightmare. Today, we have <strong>Flexbox</strong>. Flexbox is like the stage director of your fashion show.
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>By simply telling a parent container <strong>display: flex;</strong>, you instantly gain the power to align, space out, center, and wrap your HTML elements with absolute precision. No more messy floats or overlapping text. It's clean, responsive, and totally necessary for modern web design.</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-css-flexbox/what-is-css-flexbox" target="_blank" class="view-btn">17 // CSS FLEXBOX</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-flexbox-photo-gallery/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">18 // FLEXBOX PHOTO GALLERY</a>

 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-css-flexbox/review-css-flexbox" target="_blank" class="view-btn">19 // FLEXBOX FUNDAMENTALS</a>
 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-pricing-plans-layout/design-a-pricing-plans-layout-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">20 // PRICING PLANS PAGE</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-7" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 7: Advanced Tailoring (Positioning)</h2>
        <p>
            Sometimes you don't want an element to just "go with the flow" of the page. Sometimes you need a specific bow pinned <strong>exactly</strong> to the top right shoulder of your dress, no matter what. That is CSS Positioning.
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>Using properties like <strong>position: absolute;</strong>, <strong>relative</strong>, or <strong>fixed;</strong>, you can break the normal rules of the HTML document and stick things exactly where you want them on the screen. It can be tricky (just like draping fabric on a bias), but building this cat painting will give you the exact practice you need.</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
    <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-how-to-work-with-floats-and-positioning-in-css/what-are-common-use-cases-for-using-floats" target="_blank" class="view-btn">21 // FLOATS AND POSITIONING</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-intermediate-css-by-building-a-cat-painting/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">22 // CAT PAINTING</a>
<a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-house-painting/build-a-house-painting"  target="_blank" class="view-btn">23 // BUILD A HOUSE PAINTING</a>
<a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-css-positioning/review-css-positioning" target="_blank" class="view-btn">24 // CSS POSITIONING REVIEW</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-8" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 8: Seasonal Collections (CSS Variables)</h2>
        <p>
           Have you ever wanted to completely change your website's vibe from a "Spring Pastel Collection" to a "Dark Mode Winter Goth" look in just one click? That is where  <strong>CSS Variables</strong> come in. They are the ultimate wardrobe quick-change!
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>Instead of typing your favorite pink hex code (`#facee2`) fifty different times across your stylesheet, you save it as a variable in your <strong>:root</strong> selector. The <strong>:root</strong> is basically the master closet for your website.</p>
<blockquote>
    <strong>Here is the secret to theme swapping:</strong><br/>
    First, declare your color in the master closet: <br/>
    <code>:root &lcub; --main-brand-color: #facee2; &rcub;</code><br/><br/>
    Then, apply it to your dresses (elements):<br/>
    <code>h1 &lcub; color: var(--main-brand-color); &rcub;</code>
  </blockquote>

<p> If you ever want to change your entire website to a new color for a new season, you don't hunt down every single header and button. You just change the variable in the <strong>:root</strong> to a new hex code, and *boom*—the entire outfit changes instantly. It's coding magic.</p>

        <div class="resource-links">
    <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-css-variables/what-are-css-custom-properties" target="_blank" class="view-btn">25 // CSS VARIABLES</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-css-variables-by-building-a-city-skyline/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">26 // BUILD A CITY SKYLINE</a>
 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-css-variables/review-css-variables" target="_blank" class="view-btn">27 // VARIABLES FUNDAMENTALS</a>
 <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-availability-table/build-an-availability-table" target="_blank" class="view-btn">28 // AVAILABILITY TABLE</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-9" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 9: Grid Couture (CSS Grid)</h2>
        <p>
            While Flexbox is amazing for lining things up in a single row or column,  <strong>CSS Grid</strong> is for complex, two-dimensional layouts. Think of it like a highly structured bodice or a multi-page editorial magazine spread!
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>With Grid, you explicitly define how many columns and rows your webpage has, and then you just tell your HTML elements which "zones" to sit in. It gives you god-tier control over the layout of your site.</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-css-grid-by-building-a-magazine/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">08 // MAGAZINE LAYOUT</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-10" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 10: The Runway Strut (Animations)</h2>
        <p>
            We don't just want static mannequins; we want clothes that move! CSS Animations and Transforms are what bring your website to life.
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>You can use <strong>@keyframes</strong> to create a timeline of style changes (like having a button slowly pulse pink), or use <strong>transform</strong> to scale, rotate, and skew elements when a user hovers over them. It adds that buttery smooth, interactive polish that makes your site feel incredibly high-end.</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-css-animation-by-building-a-ferris-wheel/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">09 // FERRIS WHEEL</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-css-transforms-by-building-a-penguin/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">10 // HAPPY FLAPPY PENGUIN</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-11" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 11: One Size Fits All (Responsive Design)</h2>
        <p>
            In fashion, a beautiful garment should look stunning no matter the sizing. In tech, that means your website needs to look just as gorgeous on an iPhone as it does on a massive desktop monitor. This is called Responsive Design.
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>We achieve this using <strong>@media</strong> queries. They are basically conditional rules that say: "If the screen shrinks below 600px wide, change the layout from three columns down to one, and make the font a little smaller." It's how we scale haute couture down to ready-to-wear everyday sizing!</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/learn-responsive-web-design-by-building-a-piano/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">11 // RESPONSIVE PIANO</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-12" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 12: The Final Runway (Portfolio)</h2>
        <p>
            Alright, designer. You've learned your basic stitches, mixed your digital dyes, imported chic fonts, tailored your boxes, and learned how to choreograph a fully responsive layout. It is time for the final styling runway.
        </p>
  <br/><br/>
<p>In this final CSS mission, you will build out your own Personal Portfolio page. This is your digital business card and fashion house storefront. Remember, you don't have to have it perfectly finished to move on, but this is the best way to prove to yourself that you know exactly how to turn a blank white screen into something deeply, uniquely *yours*. Have fun, experiment with those hex codes, and make it cute!</p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/build-a-personal-portfolio-webpage-project/build-a-personal-portfolio-webpage" target="_blank" class="view-btn">12 // PERSONAL PORTFOLIO</a>
        </div>
    </div>


    <div class="mgrid-item" >
        <h2>Aesthetic Achieved.</h2>
           <p>CONGRATS!! You've officially styled your way through the core CSS portion of the P.C.C. curriculum! Your websites no longer look like basic outlines! They have soul, color, and structure.</p>
    </div>
    </div>

  </section>
</BaseLayout>

